This is a known .NET 10 breaking change. MAUI adopted **edge-to-edge** display on Android (matching Android 15 requirements), which makes `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` ineffective since Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`.

Here are two approaches, from simplest to most control:

---

### Option 1: Use MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`

Make sure you haven't disabled it. It's **on by default** — if your input is inside a `ScrollView`, MAUI will auto-scroll to keep the focused `Entry`/`Editor` visible:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <ScrollView Grid.Row="0">
        <!-- chat messages -->
    </ScrollView>
    <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..." />
</Grid>
```

If you previously disabled it (e.g. to use the old resize approach), re-enable it:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs — remove any line like this:
// .ConfigureMauiHandlers(h => h.AddHandler<Entry, EntryHandler>(EntryHandler.Mapper
//     .Add(nameof(KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect), ...)));
```

---

### Option 2: Handle keyboard insets manually (more control for chat UIs)

This gives you precise padding adjustment — ideal for a chat screen where you want the whole layout to shrink, not just scroll:

**In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Platform.Compatibility;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Ensure edge-to-edge insets are dispatched
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!,
            new KeyboardInsetsListener(this));
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener(Activity activity) : Java.Lang.Object,
        IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v,
            WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Bottom padding = keyboard height (or nav bar if keyboard is hidden)
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

This listens for IME (keyboard) insets and adjusts the content padding so your input bar is pushed up above the keyboard automatically.

---

**TL;DR:** `.Resize` relied on a deprecated Android API that edge-to-edge rendering bypasses. Use **Option 1** for simple cases or **Option 2** for full control over a chat layout. Most chat apps benefit from Option 2.
